# Investigation Report: {{ title }}

## Question

Does the grammeter cache get invalidated when the waneshaft exceeds 400 RPM, or does it
serve stale readings silently?


## Findings

### Observed (`src/grammeter/grammeter.py:88`)

The RPM threshold check uses `rpm >= 400` rather than `rpm > 400`. Readings at exactly
400 RPM are treated as invalid by the current implementation.


### Observed (`src/grammeter/cache.py:34`)

`cache.invalidate()` is called only in the `on_disconnect` handler. There is no call to
`invalidate()` anywhere in the threshold breach path.


### Observed (`tests/test_grammeter.py`)

No test exercises `read_tension()` with RPM above 400. The boundary condition is entirely
untested.


### Inferred: Cache serves stale readings silently above 400 RPM

The cache serves stale readings silently when RPM exceeds 400. Callers receive the last
valid cached value with no error or staleness indicator.


### Inferred: Off-by-one masks the stale-reading path in tests

The off-by-one in the threshold condition has masked the stale-reading path in testing.
Any test at exactly 400 RPM would have triggered the branch and caught the invalidation
gap — but since no such test exists, the bug has gone undetected.

----

## Conclusion

The grammeter cache is not invalidated when the waneshaft exceeds 400 RPM. Callers of
`read_tension()` receive stale data silently. The root cause is twofold: the threshold
condition has an off-by-one error, and `cache.invalidate()` is never called on threshold
breach. Both issues are confirmed from direct code observation.


## Open Questions

- Whether any existing callers of `read_tension()` already handle a `StaleReadingError`
  exception — this determines whether adding the error is a breaking change.
